  "response_text": "This is a compassionate and highly effective plan designed specifically for **burnout recovery**. The core principle here is **\"Minimum Effective Dose\"** — doing just enough to signal health to your body without triggering more stress.\n\n**Important Disclaimer:** I am an AI, not a doctor or therapist. Burnout can have physiological components (thyroid, adrenal, vitamin D, B12 deficiencies). Please consult a healthcare provider for blood work.\n\n### The Guiding Philosophy for the Week\n\n- **No HIIT. No \"Grinding.\"** High-intensity exercise is a stressor. We are avoiding cortisol spikes.\n- **Food is Fuel + Comfort.** We prioritize blood sugar stability (to prevent energy crashes) and anti-inflammatory foods.\n- **Sleep is Non-Negotiable.** If you only do one thing this week, prioritize 7.5–9 hours of sleep. Skip a workout if you are exhausted.\n- **\"Good Enough\" is Perfect.** Don't aim for perfect macros or a perfect workout. Aim for 70% consistency.\n\n---\n\n## Part 1: The Diet Plan (Stabilizing Energy)\n\n**Goal:** Steady blood sugar, reduced inflammation, and gut support.\n\n### General Rules\n- **Eat within 90 minutes of waking** to reset cortisol.\n- **Protein + Fat + Fiber at every meal** (e.g., eggs + avocado + spinach).\n- **Hydrate:** 2-3 liters of water. Dehydration mimics fatigue.\n- **Limit:** Caffeine (1 cup max, before noon), alcohol (zero), and refined sugar (causes energy crashes).\n\n### Sample Weekly Menu (Simple & Low-Effort)\n\n| Day | Breakfast (Fast) | Lunch (No-cook/Prep) | Dinner (15 min or slow cooker) | Snack (if hungry) |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Mon** | Greek yogurt + berries + walnuts | Leftover soup or sardines on toast | Salmon (baked 12 min) + frozen broccoli + sweet potato | Apple + peanut butter |\n| **Tue** | 2 scrambled eggs + 1 slice sourdough + avocado | Big salad with chickpeas, olive oil, lemon | Lentil soup (canned, add spinach) + side of chicken | Handful of almonds |\n| **Wed** | Oatmeal (rolled oats) + protein powder + banana | Tuna salad (canned) + crackers + cucumber | Ground turkey stir-fry (frozen veg + soy sauce + ginger) | Cottage cheese + pear |\n| **Thu** | Smoothie (banana, spinach, milk, protein powder, flax) | Leftover stir-fry | Baked chicken thighs + roasted carrots + quinoa | Rice cakes + hummus |\n| **Fri** | 2 hard-boiled eggs + an orange | Leftover chicken + quinoa bowl | **\"Deconstructed\" Burrito Bowl:** Ground beef, lettuce, salsa, avocado, cheese | Dark chocolate (2 squares) |\n| **Sat** | **Sleep in:** Protein shake + banana | **Easy:** Canned black beans + cheese + tortilla + hot sauce | **Treat:** Roast veggies + sausage (tray bake) | Popcorn |\n| **Sun** | Big omelet (3 eggs, leftover veggies) | Leftover tray bake | **Prep for Monday:** Make extra chicken/grains | Yogurt + honey |\n\n**Key Supplements to Discuss with a Doctor:**\n- **Magnesium Glycinate:** Helps sleep and muscle relaxation.\n- **Vitamin D + K2:** Critical for low energy.\n- **B-Complex:** For cellular energy production.\n\n---\n\n## Part 2: The Workout Routine (Rebuilding Capacity)\n\n**Goal:** Move to *feel better*, not to burn calories. We use **Zone 2** (low heart rate) and **restorative** movement.\n\n**Weekly Schedule:**\n- **3 days of \"Movement\"** (20-30 min, low intensity)\n- **2 days of \"Strength\"** (15-20 min, very light weight)\n- **2 days of \"Active Rest\"** (5-10 min stretching or walking)\n\n### The \"Movement\" Days (Mon, Wed, Fri)\n- **Option A:** Walk outside (no headphones, look at trees) for 20-30 min. Pace should be \"I could sing a song.\"\n- **Option B:** Very gentle yoga (search \"Yoga for Fatigue\" or \"Restorative Yoga\" on YouTube—Yoga with Adriene is great).\n- **Option C:** Stationary bike or elliptical. Keep heart rate under 120 bpm.\n\n### The \"Strength\" Days (Tue, Thu)\n- **Rule:** Use 50% of the weight you *think* you can do. No failure.\n- **Circuit (repeat 2-3 times, rest 60s between rounds):**\n    1.  **Goblet Squats (or Bodyweight):** 10 reps (hold a dumbbell at chest).\n    2.  **Push-ups (on knees or wall):** 8-10 reps.\n    3.  **Rows (using a band or light dumbbell):** 10 reps per arm.\n    4.  **Deadbugs (core):** 8 reps per side (slow and controlled).\n    5.  **Glute Bridge:** 12 reps (squeeze glutes at top).\n\n### The \"Active Rest\" Days (Sat, Sun)\n- **No obligation.**\n- If you feel good: 10 min foam rolling or a slow 15 min walk.\n- If you feel tired: **Do nothing.** Read a book. Nap. This is part of the recovery.\n\n---\n\n## How to Know You're Doing It Right\n\nYou should feel **slightly better** after the workout than before it.\n- **If you feel worse/drained:** You did too much. Cut the time in half or skip the next session.\n- **If you feel energized:** This is the sweet spot. Don't increase intensity yet. Stick with this for 2-3 weeks.\n\n### The \"Emergency\" Protocol (For Very Low Energy Days)\n\nIf you can barely get out of bed:\n1.  **Do 5 minutes of deep breathing** (in for 4, hold for 4, out for 4).\n2.  **Walk to the kitchen and drink a full glass of water.**\n3.  **Eat a protein-rich snack** (cheese stick, nuts, hard-boiled egg).\n4.  **Go back to bed or the couch.** You just did your workout. That counts.\n\n**Final thought:** Your body is not broken; it is exhausted. Treat it like a dear friend who is sick. You wouldn't make a sick friend run a marathon. You would bring them soup and a blanket. Be that friend to yourself this week.",
